.SH NAME
ElementInternals.ariaAtomic \- ElementInternals: ariaAtomic property
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]ariaAtomic\f[B]\f[R] property of the
\f[CR]ElementInternals\f[R] interface reflects the value of the
\f[CR]aria\-atomic\f[R] attribute, which indicates whether assistive
technologies will present all, or only parts of, the changed region
based on the change notifications defined by the
\f[CR]aria\-relevant\f[R] attribute.
.RS
.PP
\f[B]Note:\f[R] Setting aria attributes on \f[CR]ElementInternals\f[R]
allows default semantics to be defined on a custom element.
These may be overwritten by author\-defined attributes, but ensure that
default semantics are retained should the author delete those
attributes, or fail to add them at all.
For more information see the \c
.UR https://wicg.github.io/aom/explainer.html#default-semantics-for-custom-elements-via-the-elementinternals-object
Accessibility Object Model explainer
.UE \c
\&.
.RE
.SH VALUE
A string with one of the following values:
.TP
\f[B]\[dq]false\[dq]\f[R]
Assistive technologies will present only the changed node or nodes.
.TP
\f[B]\[dq]true\[dq]\f[R]
Assistive technologies will present the entire changed region as a
whole, including the author\-defined label if one exists.
.SH EXAMPLES
In this example the value of \f[CR]ariaAtomic\f[R] is set to
\[lq]true\[rq] in the constructor for a custom element.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]class\f[R] MyCustomElement \f[B]extends\f[R] HTMLElement {
  constructor() {
    \f[B]super\f[R]();
    \f[B]this\f[R].internals_ = \f[B]this\f[R].attachInternals();
    \f[B]this\f[R].internals_.ariaAtomic = \[dq]true\[dq];
  }
}
.EE
